"Before erasers became a stock pencil accessory in 1858, you might not be surprised to see a writer carrying a around a stale baguette with his papers and gear. That‚Äôs because breadcrumbs were the writing world‚Äôs most popular erasers from 1612 to 1770. The first rubber eraser was allegedly used by accident when a writer was reaching for his crumbs, and instead picked up a hunk of what the French called caoutchouc‚Äîa stretchy sample of the newly-discovered Para tree. The substance proved great for rubbing pencil marks off of paper. Since then, we‚Äôve called it rubber." #FunFactFriday #BackToSchool

https://www.rd.com/article/pencils-history/

shared_text:
Willcox Elementary School Home of the Cowkids
September 3 at 7:33 AM ¬∑

Good morning Cowkid Families!

We are noticing that some students are not logging on to Schoology during the days that students are at home. For clarification, students who attend school in-person on Mondays and Wednesdays MUST log on to Schoology and Zoom on Tuesdays and Thursdays. Students who attend school in-person on Tuesdays and Thursdays MUST log on to Schoology and Zoom on Mondays and Wednesdays. Students who do not log on are counted absent.

Schoology and Zoom are the necessary instruction for your students' learning on their at-home days. Even if your child brings home written assignments to complete, they must still log on. Please contact your child's teacher if you are having problems logging on.

Thank you for your continued support of your child's education at WES.

"At standard temperature and pressure, helium weighs about 0.18g/litre, and air 1.29g/litre. The difference is what a litre of helium should lift: 1.11g. So 1000 litres lifts a little over a kilogram, and a 70kg (154 Ib) human needs around 70,000 litres: very roughly 10,000 normal balloons, or approximately 300 of those party balloon cylinders at supermarkets. ‚ÄòCluster ballooning‚Äô aficionados use 50-150 balloons, each larger ‚Äì over a metre wide ‚Äì than a standard balloon. Not one to try at home though."

#FunFactFriday

https://www.sciencefocus.com/science/how-many-helium-balloons-would-it-take-to-make-me-float/

post_text: Congratulations, Dakota! Your hard work and innovation is incredible!
shared_text:
Willcox High School
August 27 at 10:29 AM ¬∑

On August 25, Dakota Finley, a 2020 graduate of WHS was selected as a recipient of the Governor's GCOI Future Innovator of the Year award for her project, Plasphalt Phase 2. Dakota worked with industry experts and community support to create an asphalt mix design substituting recycled HDPE plastic for aggregate. In demonstrating the viability of her design, a teacher's parking lot was donated last February. Since then, Dakota has worked with CMT Laboratories in Tucson, measuring the properties of the "Plasphalt".

All students across the state were invited to compete with their science fair submissions. Four were selected the best among all entries, and Dakota really stood out!

Way to go WILLCOX!!

"Mauna Kea, a volcanic mountain on the island of Hawaii, has an altitude of 4,207 meters (13,803 feet) - much lower than Mount Everest. However, Mauna Kea is an island, and if the distance from the bottom of the nearby Pacific Ocean floor to the peak of the island is measured, then Mauna Kea is "taller" than Mount Everest.

Mauna Kea is over 10,000 meters tall compared to 8,848 meters for Mount Everest - making it the "world's tallest mountain.""

#FunFactFriday

https://geology.com/records/highest-mountain-in-the-world.shtml

The governing board recently voted to resume in-person class instruction on Monday, August 17. We know this is a relief for many parents but raises concerns for others. We want to address all questions and concerns but cannot do that in one letter. Please contact your school, email teachers or principals with questions, or you can always contact the superintendent. We can accommodate most learning scenarios should you not feel comfortable sending your student back just yet.

Please follow the link below for more information and complete details regarding our return to in-person class instruction as posted earlier.

post_text: Here is an update from WES regarding A/B schedule starting Monday!
shared_text:
Willcox Elementary School Home of the Cowkids
August 13 at 6:15 PM ¬∑

WES Families,
We will begin school in-person, using our A/B schedule on Monday, August 17.

Buses will run, although we do not yet have the complete schedules. If your child rides a bus, plan to be at their bus stop early so you don't miss the bus.

The cafeteria will serve breakfast and lunch.

If you bring your child to school, please be aware that parents will not be allowed to enter campus beyond the office.

Students with a last name beginning with A-L should arrive on Monday. Students with a last name beginning with M-Z should arrive on Tuesday. We will continue the staggered schedule so that half of our students are at school on Mondays and Wednesdays, and the other half on Tuesdays and Thursdays.

We appreciate your patience as we begin a new school year, and we are truly excited to see our students and begin this year's learning journey!

As always, if you have questions you can call the school office at 384-8603, Monday-Thursday from 7am - 5pm.

See you next week!
Mrs. Simon

As the school year starts, we want to help make sure that our students return to school feeling the best that they can. If your child is feeling nervous or anxious, about school or about their world right now, we have counseling services with our district counselor, Mrs. Singer, and our counselor-in-training, Miss Hayes. If you think your child could benefit from counseling, please call the WES office at (520) 384-8603.

"Until now it was believed the nose, with its 400 olfactory receptors, could detect only about 10,000 different odours.

Scientists at the Rockefeller University, New York, set out to test the idea, which dates back to 1927 and was never scientifically investigated.

They estimated that the average person can discriminate between at least one trillion different odours with the nose, far more than can be detected by the eye or ear.
This is probably an underestimate, they say."

#FunFactFriday

Read more here:https://www.bbc.com/news/health-26638085

July 13 at 11:21 AM ¬∑

WHS is currently providing registration packets at the office for all returning WHS students and students who were promoted from 8th grade at WMS last year. The packet must be completed and turned in at registration the week of 7/27. Students may not receive their schedule or check out a Chromebook (if they don't have a computer or tablet at home) if their registration packet isn't completed, signed and turned in. Packets are also available to new students to the district (this does not include Cochise/Bonita students who attended our Freshman Roundup in February). Stop by and pick up a packet at the table by the office door and highlight your name on the list provided if you're a returning student (or incoming Freshman from WMS). If you have any questions, please don't hesitate to contact Ms. Hall at tammy.hall@wusd13.org. Thank you for your continued patience and support during this time - GO COWBOYS

post_text:
June is National Safety Month!

Identifying risks around the home, or improving safety standards at home and in your community protects everyone. Whether we increase first aid and emergency awareness through drills, or provide water safety tips for summer recreation, we are taking steps to provide a safer neighborhood.

How to observe #NationalSafetyMonth:

Get involved!
- Report repairs as they are needed
- Hold drills at home to help children know what to do in the event of
- fire
- tornado
- medical event
- another natural disaster
- Volunteer to participate in community emergency preparedness events
- Put together a first aid kit
- Take a CPR class
- Teach someone to change a tire properly and safely
- Learn about proper storage and disposal of medications
- Take a defensive driving course
- Learn how to identify fall hazards in a home
- Visit the National Safety Council website for tips and resources and use #NationalSafetyMonth to share on social media.

https://nationaldaycalendar.com/national-safety-month-june/

Here are some great tips to help students manage their digital footprint.

"Simply put, a digital footprint is the record or trail left by the things you do online. Your social media activity, the info on your personal website, your browsing history, your online subscriptions, any photo galleries and videos you‚Äôve uploaded ‚Äî essentially, anything on the Internet with your name on it. Digital natives like today‚Äôs students rarely think twice about putting their names on things online, so their footprints can be pretty wide."

Read more here: https://tinyurl.com/ybtyqrv3

Did you know you can estimate the temperature by counting a cricket's chirps? It's true!

"The frequency of chirping varies according to temperature. To get a rough estimate of the temperature in degrees fahrenheit, count the number of chirps in 15 seconds and then add 37. The number you get will be an approximation of the outside temperature."

https://www.loc.gov/everyday-mysteries/item/can-you-tell-the-temperature-by-listening-to-the-chirping-of-a-cricket/

post_text: We will miss you, Mr. and Mrs. Downs!
shared_text:
Willcox Elementary School Home of the Cowkids
May 19 at 3:35 PM ¬∑

Today our staff recognized Mr. and Mrs. Downs, before they leave us to move to Coolidge.

Mr. Downs, we will miss your puppet shows and Motown revues, and your students will definitely miss how you always find a special nickname to use when you call on them in class and the many ways you engage them in learning!

Mrs. Downs, we will miss your smile and friendly nature, and your students will surely miss your special morning greeting for each of them, along with the many ways you kept them actively learning those kindergarten skills!

Both Mr. and Mrs. Downs have given their time, their hearts, and their dedication to the students of Willcox. We are grateful that you were a part of our WES staff for the past 4 years!

"The origin of the term Uncle Sam, though disputed, is usually associated with a businessman from Troy, New York, Samuel Wilson, known affectionately as ‚ÄúUncle Sam‚Äù Wilson. The barrels of beef that he supplied the army during the War of 1812 were stamped ‚ÄúU.S.‚Äù to indicate government property. That identification is said to have led to the widespread use of the nickname Uncle Sam for the United States, and a resolution passed by Congress in 1961 recognized Wilson as the namesake of the national symbol."

https://www.britannica.com/topic/Uncle-Sam

#FunFactFriday

post_text:
"Yep, you read that right. Concocting jelly beans requires many steps. First, liquid sugar and flavors are heated and mixed with starch and glucose. This is poured into bean-shaped starch molds and left to dry overnight. The next day, the starch is removed and the beans go through a steam bath and get sprayed with sugar. Next, they undergo what candy makers call "panning." They're put into a machine with a rotating drum, and while they spin, colors and flavors are added. Finally, grains of sugar are poured in‚Äîthis sugar creates the bean's hard shell. As a finishing touch, hot syrup and wax are applied to give shine. After all this shaking and making, the beans are thoroughly dried before they are packaged and shipped."

https://www.rd.com/food/fun/jelly-beans-facts/

#FunFactFriday
text:
"Yep, you read that right. Concocting jelly beans requires many steps. First, liquid sugar and flavors are heated and mixed with starch and glucose. This is poured into bean-shaped starch molds and left to dry overnight. The next day, the starch is removed and the beans go through a steam bath and get sprayed with sugar. Next, they undergo what candy makers call "panning." They're put into a machine with a rotating drum, and while they spin, colors and flavors are added. Finally, grains of sugar are poured in‚Äîthis sugar creates the bean's hard shell. As a finishing touch, hot syrup and wax are applied to give shine. After all this shaking and making, the beans are thoroughly dried before they are packaged and shipped."

"During April, buds come into full bloom brightening our days, and National Month of Hope also lends a hand in lifting our spirits.

Bringing hope to someone can take many forms. Being a positive role model in the life of a child or providing a community a foundation for future endeavors both provide hope for the future. Lift the spirits of a friend suffering from a medical issue or volunteer at a local homeless shelter. We are each able to bring a ray of hope in our own ways by contributing wisdom, time, kindness and when possible donate to charities that make the impossible possible."

https://nationaldaycalendar.com/national-month-of-hope-april/

"All but the first floors of most buildings in Pompeii were destroyed during the eruption of Mount Vesuvius, but vertical pipes leading to lost second stories suggest that there were toilets upstairs in some buildings. Scrapings from the insides of these pipes revealed fecal material and traces of intestinal parasites.

‚ÄúWe have 23 [surviving] toilets that are connected, that are second-story preserved, that are connected to these downpipes,‚Äù said A. Kate Trusler of the University of Missouri at the annual meeting of the Archaeological Institute of America. Her survey of Pompeii‚Äôs plumbing found that 43 percent of homes had latrines on the ground floor. The second-story toilets were found in a heavily populated area where people probably lived above street-level shops."

https://www.archaeology.org/news/443-130114-pompeii-plumbing-secondfloor

Happy #PiDay tomorrow!

"Though it wasn‚Äôt called pi until the 18th century, the numerical relationship between a circle‚Äôs diameter and circumference has been pondered since antiquity.

In the second millennium B.C., the Babylonians used 25/8 for pi (equivalent to 3.125), while the Egyptians are believed to have used 256/81 (equivalent to 3.160).

In a pair of passages in the Bible (1 Kings 7:23 and 2 Chronicles 4:2), the altar in King Solomon‚Äôs temple is said to be ‚Äú10 cubits from brim to brim‚Äù while ‚Äú30 cubits did compass it round about‚Äù ‚Äîdimensions that seem to place the value of what we now call pi at 3.

The symbol œÄ was first used to denote the circumference-to-diameter ratio in 1706 by Welsh mathematician William Jones. But it didn‚Äôt catch on until Swiss mathematician Leonhard Euler adopted its use in the 1730s."

https://www.nbcnews.com/mach/science/pi-day-7-interesting-facts-about-most-famous-number-mathemathics-ncna982141

2020 TV/Video Production Region Six Team Competition
The 2020 SkillsUSA TV/Video Production Region Six Team Competition was held Friday, January 31st in Tucson. Region Six consist of 26 southern Arizona high schools that can enter five teams of two students per school. Only the top 10 teams from the region qualify for state competition that will be held April 27th & 28th in Phoenix. Willcox High School qualified all five video production teams for state. Placing 4th were Lynden Smyer & KJ Jones, Regional Runner-Ups were Sydney Hansen & Khezia Perolino, and the 2020 TV/Video Production Regional Champions were Santana Fuentes & Megan Bohr. Also qualifying for state were Lexie Morales & Cael De Baun, and Lilly Friend & Lilian German. WHS‚Äôs audio/visual instructor and sponsor is Dr. Doug Miller.

- The Invisible Man by Ralph Ellison
- The Fire Next Time by James Baldwin
- Native Son by Richard Wright

Use #BlackHistoryMonth on social media and start a book discussion."

"The archipelago‚Äôs Spanish name Islas Canarias is derived from the Latin phrase Canariae Insulae which means the "island of dogs." King Juba II of Mauretania, an ancient Kingdom in the Maghreb, is thought to have named the island of Grand Canaria due to the presence of many large dogs on the island. Eventually, the entire archipelago became referred to as the Canary Islands.

Another possible theory is that the name was derived from the Guanches who were the original inhabitants of the Canary Islands. The Guanches treated dogs as holy animals, worshipping and mummifying them. There is thought to be a connection between the dog-worship of the Guanches and Anubis, the dog-headed Egyptian god."

https://www.worldatlas.com/articles/did-you-know-that-the-canary-islands-are-named-after-dogs.html

"In a study published last week in Science Advances, researchers from UC Berkeley and Durham University examined the pupil shapes of goats ‚Äî and of 213 other land species ‚Äî to look for patterns. They found that ecological niche ‚Äî in other words, whether you're the hunter or the hunted ‚Äî is a great predictor of how your eyes will be shaped. It's not an entirely new idea, but now they've confirmed the trend in a large number of species, and taken a closer look at how important the variation might be."

https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/speaking-of-science/wp/2015/08/10/heres-why-goats-have-those-freaky-eyes/
